&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The most appropriate meaning of the underlined idiom&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;put his foot down&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; in the given sentence is&lt;strong&gt; option 3) refused to yield.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The idiom &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;put one&amp;#39;s foot down&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;means &lt;strong&gt;to assert one&amp;#39;s authority, make a firm decision, or refuse to give in to someone else&amp;#39;s demands or requests.&lt;/strong&gt; In the given sentence, the speaker is pleading with someone to reconsider their application, but the person &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;put his foot down,&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;indicating that they refused to change their decision and did not yield to the speaker&amp;#39;s plea.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, &lt;strong&gt;option 3) &amp;quot;refused to yield&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is the most appropriate meaning for the underlined idiom &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;put his foot down&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; as it aligns with the context of the sentence, indicating a firm refusal or decision.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

